### Type Aliases

Type aliases create a new name for a type. They can represent any type, not just object shapes.

### Basic Syntax

```typescript
type Age = number;
type Name = string;
type IsActive = boolean;

let age: Age = 30;
```

### Object Types

```typescript
type User = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email?: string;
};

const user: User = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30
};
```

### Union Types

```typescript
type Status = "active" | "inactive" | "pending";
type Id = string | number;
type Nullable<T> = T | null;
```

### Function Types

```typescript
type Callback = (error: Error | null, result?: unknown) => void;
type MathOp = (a: number, b: number) => number;

const add: MathOp = (a, b) => a + b;
```

### Generic Type Aliases

```typescript
type Result<T> = {
  success: true;
  data: T;
} | {
  success: false;
  error: string;
};

const success: Result<string> = {
  success: true,
  data: "Operation completed"
};
```

### Type Alias vs Interface

| Feature | Type Alias | Interface |
|---------|-----------|-----------|
| Object shapes | Yes | Yes |
| Union types | Yes | No |
| Mapped types | Yes | No |
| Declaration merging | No | Yes |
| Extends | Intersection (&) | extends keyword |

> **Key Point:** Type aliases can represent any type, including primitives, unions, and tuples.

codeExample:
// Primitive alias
type ID = string;
type Coordinate = number;

// Union alias
type Result<T> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: string };

// Function alias
type Transformer<T, U> = (input: T) => U;

const toString: Transformer<number, string> = (n) => n.toString();

// Complex generic type
type ApiResponse<T> = {
  data: T;
  status: number;
  message: string;
};

// Mapped type alias
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [P in keyof T]: T[P];
};
